@node "Introduction" "Introduction"

        Please, read @{"node about links" link "Links" 0} first if you don't know what is it all
about :) Now, if you know what link is I can tell you, that @{fg shine}FileLinker@{fg text} is a
program for nice creating such links on the disks. You can do this much
simplier then using CLI command @{i}MakeLink@{ui}. @{fg shine}File Linker@{fg text} opens a small window
and let's you choose file and link very easy, with requester or appicon.

        But @{fg shine}FileLinker@{fg text} has some disadvanteges eighter :( First and last it
cannot create soft-link (all links are hard-links). It's not my fault, but
DOS's which cannot yet make any soft-link. @{i}MakeLink()@{ui} function always
returns NIL :( I don't know how soft-links are made with CLI command
@{i}MakeLink@{ui}, but after disassembling you can see, that options for @{i}MakeLink()@{ui}
function is always set to @{b}HARD@{ub}. I'll try to fix this problem i future
realises.

        If you are intrested in links and problems with using it, just read
@{"this chapter" link "BadLinks" 0}.
@endnode

@node "Links" "What hte heck is that?"

        Links are very useful on our operating system (but they also are on
other system, link OS/2, Unix etc.). With links you can easily have one file
in many other places, without free space problem. Every link takes just one
block (512 bytes) and it doesn't matter is file big or very short. BTW: You
can make links to directories too!

        But there's one restriction. @{b}Links can be made only on one device!@{ub}
It's of course not possible to make link from DH0: to DH1: etc. If you want
to read some notes and warnings about links, read @{"this chapter" link "BadLinks" 0}.
@endnode

@node "BadLinks" "Problems and restrictions"

        When making links you must be prepared for some problems and
restrictions. You should be very careful with deleting, copying, changing
files and directories. I think there are few most important notes about it:

1. Remember witch files are links and witch are original. If you operate
with links you can be sure that everything will be OK. But if you delete the
original file, all links will be deleted. More, because of bug (?) in
AmigaDOS there can appeare some checksum errors, while reading directory.
Then you must delete all that "trashlinks" by hand, and then all problems
should disappear.

2. @{b}Links to diretories can be very dangerous!@{ub} Always remember, that deleting
files from linked directory is the same, as deleting files from original! I
don't know how to delete unused dir-link from disk so far. But I think it's
possible...

3. Little note: You cannot set the comment for link. It's a pity, 'cause it
could be very useful :( Unfortunatly, every commant will be automaticly
"meved" to original file :(
@endnode

@node "Instructions" "Instructions"

        Program opens small, standard window on the Workbench. The most
important gadgets, are string gadgets, where you can type in names for file
and link to be created. If you think names are OK, just click on the "@{fg shine}Make
Link@{fg text}" gadget and link automaticly will be created. But please, read the @{"doc" link "Links" 0}
@{"about links" link "Links" 0} first!

        If you'd like to choose files easier you can use program's appicon.
If tou'll drag ther any icon, the name of this file will be automaticly
sended to @{fg shine}File@{fg text} gadget. If you'll grad two icons at once, name of the second
file will be sended to @{fg shine}Link@{fg text} gadget. If it's still problem for you, you can
simply choose file from standard ASL filerequester. Just click on the one of
th S gadgets, that are placed at the right side of the window. You can use
shortcuts: @{fg fill}<Shift+f>@{fg text}=select file, @{fg fill}<Shift+l>@{fg text}=select link.

        There's of course some shortcuts for other gadgets. @{fg fill}<Shift+m>@{fg text}=Make
Link, @{fg fill}<s>@{fg text}=Sleep, @{fg fill}<f>@{fg text}=type in file, @{fg fill}<l>@{fg text}=type in link. That's all about keys.

        One note about @{fg shine}sleep@{fg text} option. To "wake up" program sinply click twice
at it's appicon or drag any icon there. Program's window will open at the
moment. If you want to quit - click on the close window gadget or press
@{fg fill}<Esc>@{fg text} key. Ok, now you can work with @{fg shine}File Linker@{fg text} without any problems (i
hope :)
@endnode

@node "Requirements" "System requirements"

        Program runs on every Amiga with KS2.0+. It was tested on:

A1200, KS3.0, Blizzard III turbo, 10MB RAM, HDD Conner 1GB

        It was made in Amiga E 3.1i. Source code is 21kb long and binary is
abou 11kb long. No non-standard libraries are needed, but ASL (wich is a
part of the standard disk-OS).
@endnode

